<div data-post-date-group="" data-post-info="">
      <p><span>Published:</span>
        <time datetime="2026-06-26T07:40:26">June 26, 2026, 7:40 pm</time>
      </p>
        <p><i role="presentation">
  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path stroke="none" d="M0 0h24v24H0z" fill="none"></path><path d="M6 6v6a3 3 0 0 0 3 3h10l-4 -4m0 8l4 -4"></path></svg>
</i>          <span>Last updated:</span>
          <time datetime="2026-06-26T07:45:46">June 26, 2026, 7:45 pm</time>
        </p>
    </div>
    <article>
      <p>This week on Aftermath Hours, Chris, Gita and Luke get together to talk about Chris's mammoth review for the <a href="https://aftermath.site/steam-machine-review-price/" rel="noreferrer">Steam Machine</a>. Then, we pose the question: Is <em>Grand Theft Auto VI</em> going to be the last big video game?</p><p>The Steam Machine is $1,049 USD, but unfortunately that's kind of just what computers cost now. Chris <em>does</em> make it sound like a really cool little PC, but in this economy?</p><p>This conversation leads into the looming release of <a href="https://aftermath.site/gta-6-physical-copies-have-no-disc/" rel="noreferrer"><em>Grand Theft Auto VI</em></a>, which hangs over us all like the sword of Damocles. Can the industry support another <a href="https://aftermath.site/grand-theft-auto-vi-games-industry/" rel="noreferrer">huge video game release</a> after this game comes out?  And why does none of it strike a chord with Luke, who is ostensibly a <em>GTA </em>guy?</p><p>Then we hit the mailbag for a surprisingly robust discussion of the merits of the Ghost CMS, among other things.</p><p>You can find this week's episode below and on <a href="https://open.spotify.com/show/7qtlX6MNeEoyNuHBU0chUJ?si=a2f12b75911f43cb&amp;ref=aftermath.site"><u>Spotify</u></a>, <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/aftermath-hours/id1727407094?ref=aftermath.site"><u>Apple</u></a>, or wherever else you prefer to listen to podcasts. If you like what you hear, leave a review!</p>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->

<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<figure><a href="https://aftermath.site/steam-machine-review-price/"><div><p>The Steam Machine Is An Iconoclastic Computer Born In Unforgiving Times</p><p>Valve has released a tiny, silent, entry level PC that does important work bringing PCs gaming to the living room and desktop Linux to the masses. The timing could not be worse.</p><p><span>Chris Person</span></p></div></a></figure>
    </article>

        

      

          

        

        

  
